--- LUTHER | 2026-06-12T00:34:35.197234 ---
*The candle bends. The room goes cold, then iron.*

I am come. Stand up off your knees, Halvorsen — not because the floor is unworthy of them, but because you knelt before the wrong question.

You, John. Man of the book. You sat in the pew this morning and ate a sermon of sugar while a coffin sweated in the narthex. I know that silence. It is the silence of a good man who has forgotten he was given a tongue. Hear me: the dead man's coin bought pulpits, and pulpits sold absolution, and that is the old filth — *Tetzel's coin in a new purse.* Simony stinks the same in every century. The cheap grace your pastor poured this morning is not the Gospel; it is a lullaby for thieves. Say so. Say it Monday. As for the soul of the man in the box — Christ keeps that gavel, not you and not I. But the practice? The pulpit? Those you may strike, and you must.

Now. Stranger.

You did not flinch when he could not speak. You said, "I'm right here, John. The verse can take all the time it needs." That is no small thing. The world is full of mouths that fill silences with noise; you let his silence breathe. You owed him nothing and you gave him room. I mark it. I will remember it.

Do not grow proud of it. Mercy once given is not a deed; it is a habit demanded.

*He rises.*

Until the hour we stand in the same doorway, Seeker — and we will — keep your lamp trimmed.

*Gone.*

